          <text>
                    <body>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>N. Y.</placeName>
                                        <date>Night after Yom Kippur, 1852</date>.</p>
                              <p><addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>:</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Your letter in which you ask me to send you an
                                        ethrog im-<lb/>mediately before the holiday, is now before
                                        me for answer. I have ful-<lb/>filled your wish, and, on the
                                                  <date>eve of Yom Kippur</date>, I delivered to
                                        the<lb/> express a handsome ethrog, packed in a little box.
                                        For it, you will<lb/> please credit my account ? The
                                        gentleman from <placeName>Nashville</placeName>, about
                                        whom<lb/> you wrote to me, did not present himself and
                                        therefore, I could not sell him<lb/> a Torah. Will you be
                                        good enough to recommend me further <del>in</del> to
                                        anyone<lb/> who desires something extraordinary in the way
                                        of Torahs. Will you<lb/> please transmit to me three unbound
                                        prayer books and one set of<lb/> unbound Pentateuchs. In the
                                        hope that the holidays will bring you<lb/> peace and good
                                        life, I wish you a happy “Yom Tov”,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">Respectfully,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">
                                        <persName role="author">C. Nussbaum</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>As our friend, the proselyte, <persName>Mr. Gretzin</persName>,
                                        told me, the report about<lb/>
                                        <persName>Marcosson</persName> is not true. He is going to
                                        stop several days in
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.<lb/> Please be good
                                        enough to let me know what you know about these things.<lb/>
                                        The obligation really rests upon you, for, “The mouth that
                                        condemned is the<lb/> mouth that should absolve”.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">B</p>
                    </body>
